            <h2>Why Massey may be a good start to your property journey</h2>
            <h6>Massey, the large north west Auckland suburb is attracting buyers with its affordable house prices and amenities.</h6>
            <div class="fakeimg" style="height:150px;">
                When Universal Homes bought 42 hectares of green fields in the north western Auckland suburb of Massey in 2017, a site known as West Hills, there wasn’t too much going on, on the new housing front.

                Universal Homes CEO Andrew Crosby says he has plans for 1400 homes at the West Hills subdivision on Westgate Drive Extension, and, if the house building company puts in some four or five storey apartment buildings, this might go up to 1500 or 1600. So far, 94 homes have been sold and settled, another 76 are to come this year and another 150 next year.

                At West Hills, Universal Homes is adhering to a Green City Living masterplan with neighbourhood parks, reserves, walkways and cycleways. The homes are architecturally designed, with walk up apartments selling at $699,999 and terraced homes starting in the mid to high $700,000s – pretty affordable by Auckland standards.

                “In West Hills, we’re definitely more affordable than Hobsonville Point, where Universal has built 900 homes,” says Andrew. “Massey is closer to the CBD by road (17 km vs 23 km) and we’ve got a massive shopping centre across the road,” he adds.

                With new housing and more people moving into the area, Universal is looking to create a community at West Hills. “We’ve got a 5000 sq m park coming,” says Andrew.

                “We’ve bought into the Massey growth of population, and the development of new shopping. It was lower decile but it’s continuously improving as more are buying in the area,” says the Universal Homes CEO.

                Once a busway comes in, a bus-only lane going into the CBD and beyond, that will be a major piece of progress, adds Andrew.
            </div>


