            <h2>Why Hobsonville Point is attracting buyers at all levels</h2>
            <h5>The master-planned community of Hobsonville Point and its relaxed lifestyle is drawing a wide range of buyers.</h5>
            <div class="fakeimg" style="height:100px;">
                Prestige real estate agent, Michael Tromp, says his family was one of the first 50 to move to Hobsonville Point, the master-planned community on a pretty peninsula jutting out into the Waitemata Harbour, which came into being from 2011.

                Previously an air base, the 26 ha township in the Waitakere region, built by a select group of top builders, is 23 km from Auckland and a 30 –35 minute ferry ride from the CBD, and it’s becoming an increasingly popular place to live for Aucklanders.

                People moved into the first homes at Hobsonville Point from around 2012. Michael and his wife sold their first home last year, moving on to a larger three bedroom place and they’ve got a three bedroom rental too.

                Michael says the prices on the homes he’s owned have gone up about 13.5 % every year. They sold their first place last November (which they bought in 2011 for $220,000) for just under $1 million. They paid $660,000 for their next home which is now worth over double what they paid.

                “I’ve had three homes in the area, I’ve lived here since day one, I’ve seen it all grow and it’s a great sight,” says Michael.

                The township has 6,250 people living there in 2,333 homes and will have 11,000 residents by 2024 in 4,500 homes, the community’s website says.
